 is the investigation of Enlightenment influences on the more well-known aspects of Macaulay's thought: history, politics, social and economic issues, religion, revolution and colonialism. The book also offers new revelations about Macaulay's attitude towards women, and provides insight into his views on art, nature and animals.In this study, Macaulay emerges as a more subversive, at times even radical, figure than previously assumed. The book thus emphasizes the transformation of Enlightenment ideas into early nineteenth-century liberalism.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAuthors, EnglishvBiographyy19th century. 0aEnlightenmentzGreat Britain. 0aHistoriansvBiographyzGreat Britain. 0aHistorianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aLiberalismzGreat Britain. 0aPoliticiansvBiographyzGreat Britain. 0aPoliticianszGreat BritainvBiography. 0aStatesmenvBiographyzGreat Britain. 0aStatesmenzGreat BritainvBiography. 4aModern History. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh  aBritish liberal culture.  aEnlightenment ideas.  aEnlightenment.  aIndia.  aMember of Parliament.  aThomas Babington Macaulay.  agovernment minister.  aideas of Enlightenment.  alegal reforms.  anineteenth-century liberalism.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertBoydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311143099740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781800106192?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781800106192423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781800106192/original  a978-3-11-143099-7  Boydell and Brewer Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles